# Wave Changelog & Commits

When a **wave** (or agreed milestone) is tested and DoD is met:

## 1. Ask before commit

Ask explicitly, e.g. “Wave N tested. Commit and update changelog?”

Do **not** commit until the user says yes.

## 2. Gather git context (readonly)

```bash
git config user.name
git branch --show-current
git status -sb
git diff
git log -5 --oneline
```

## 3. Commit (on approval)

- Stage only relevant files (no secrets).
- Message: concise why-focused (1–2 sentences), HEREDOC per user git rules.
- Prefer one commit per completed wave unless user requests otherwise.

## 4. Changelog (same approval)

Update both:

1. **`CHANGELOG.md`** — short Keep a Changelog entry under `[Unreleased]` or new version section.
2. **`docs/changelogs/WAVE-XX.md`** — copy `docs/changelogs/TEMPLATE.md` and fill:

| Field | Source |
|---|---|
| **Who** | `git config user.name` (+ email if useful) |
| **Where** | branch name + optional commit SHA after commit |
| **When** | ISO date |
| **Why** | product/tech reason for the wave |
| **What** | bullet list of features, files, APIs, tests |
| **How verified** | pytest commands, Admin/Swagger checks, compose smoke |
| **Wave** | W0–W6 id + plan path |

## 5. Master plan

Check off the wave in `docs/plans/2026-07-23-master-implementation-plan.md`.
